## Test Cases

### Basic SSH Connectivity
1. Connect to worker:
   - Verify SSH connection established
   - Verify key authentication works
   - Verify connection closes cleanly
   - Log: connection attempt, auth result, close status

2. Connection timeout:
   - Test with invalid host
   - Verify timeout occurs within budget
   - Verify graceful error handling
   - Log: timeout value, actual wait, error type

3. Connection pooling:
   - Multiple commands reuse connection
   - Connections cleaned up on daemon shutdown
   - Pool does not leak connections
   - Log: pool stats before/after each command

### SSH Key Handling
4. Key authentication:
   - Test with default ~/.ssh/id_rsa
   - Test with custom key path
   - Verify key passphrase handling (or skip)
   - Log: key path used (not content!), key type

5. Known hosts:
   - Verify known hosts checked (or bypassed safely)
   - Handle new host fingerprint
   - Log: fingerprint validation status

### Connection Resilience
6. Reconnection:
   - Kill connection, verify reconnect
   - Verify in-flight command handled
   - Log: disconnect, reconnect attempts, success

7. Multiple workers:
   - Connect to multiple workers simultaneously
   - Verify independent connection state
   - Log: per-worker connection state

## Security Note
NEVER log actual key content or passphrases. Only log:
- Key file paths
- Key types (ed25519, rsa, ecdsa)
- Fingerprints (if shown to user anyway)

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] SSH connections work to real workers
- [ ] Key authentication succeeds
- [ ] Connection pooling reduces overhead
- [ ] Timeouts handled gracefully
- [ ] No connection leaks
